The '''National Anti-Gambling League''' ('''NAGL''') was a British campaigning organization founded in 1890 by F. A. Atkins. The aims of the NAGL were laid out in its journal, the ''Bulletin of the National Anti-Gambling League'':
{{quote|Nothing less than the reformation of England as regards the particular vice against which our efforts are aimed... There is humiliation in the thought that the chosen Anglo Saxon race, foremost in the civilisation and government of the world, is first also in the great sin of [[Gambling]].<ref name="Orford2003">{{cite book|author=Jim Orford|title=Gambling and Problem Gambling in Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mj5_Xwcvk20C&pg=PA6|year=2003|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-1-58391-923-1|pages=6–}} Quoting ''Bulletin  of the National Anti-Gambling League'', vol. 1, no. 7, p.1.</ref>}}

NAGL Members included John Hawke, [[J. A. Hobson]], [[Ramsay MacDonald]] and [[Seebohm Rowntree]].<ref name="Munting1996">{{cite book|author=Roger Munting|title=An Economic and Social History of Gambling in Britain and the USA|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ByboAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA25|year=1996|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=978-0-7190-4449-6|page=25}}</ref>

